=======================
TODAY IN HEALTH HISTORY
=======================

Magnifying Life

On this date in 1949, two doctors saw something new.  Daniel C.
Pease and Richard F. Baker, both assistant professors at the
University of Southern California, used a regular electronic
microscope and a cutting technique they developed to magnify the
tissue of a fruit fly 120,000 times.  What they saw was a
spindle-shaped object 1-100,000th of a centimeter long and 1-1-
millionth of a centimeter wide.  It was the first sighting of a
gene.  The New York Times, at the time, reported that "the
observation ... is expected to be of great importance in medical
and biological research, particularly in connection with germs
and viruses."

Copyright Aetna InteliHealth, Inc., 2003.  All rights reserved.

