Obesity In Middle Age Cuts Years Off Life

PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- People who are overweight at 40 are likely
to die at least three years sooner than those who are slim,
meaning that in terms of life expectancy, being fat during middle
age is just as bad as smoking, researchers say.

http://www.intelihealth.com/IH/ihtIH/EMIHC000/333/333/359831.html

For more on weight management, visit our featured area:
http://www.intelihealth.com/IH/ihtIH/WSIHW000/14220/14220.html
_


Diabetes Benefit Doesn't Offset Hormone Risk

(USA TODAY) -- Taking postmenopausal hormones cut women's risk of
developing diabetes by 35%, but that's no reason to go on the
therapy, a study concludes today.

http://www.intelihealth.com/IH/ihtIH/EMIHC000/333/333/359826.html

For more on diabetes, visit our featured area:
http://www.intelihealth.com/IH/ihtIH/WSIHW000/21054/21054.html
_


States' Anti-Tobacco Spending Criticized

NEW YORK (AP) -- The American Lung Association is criticizing
states for using tobacco settlement money to cover budget
deficits instead of anti-smoking programs.

http://www.intelihealth.com/IH/ihtIH/EMIHC000/333/333/359829.html


